bug.short_desc: Erratic character display with larger font size in Chrome Browser

long_desc.thetext:
I have noticed that when I increase the display size of fonts (^+) that there is a very inconsistent resultant number of characters displayed in the character fields of the graphical nodes in the tree (left column) (in the Chrome Browser).
See attached image
For example the entire word 'ObjectRegistry' somehow finds room but the shorter term "Init" simply disappears and is replaced with "...".
This is NOT true for FireFox.
Using Chrome 9.0.597.84

Created attachment 904 Screen Capture with the Chrome Browser in the left window...
Shows the inconsistent "degradation" at the nodes as per the bug description.

Thanks for the report. Increasing the font size is not really supported by qooxdoo but still, could not reproduce the issue in Chrome devel on mac. Did you try to realod with the increased font width? Thats usually trigger the layout system to render correctly.
Created attachment 1009 Normal version of our GUI
Created attachment 1010 Bugged version of our GUI

Added two attachments showing our GUI displayed under normal conditions and under some very specific conditions. You can easily understand why we'd like the bugged version never to appear in front of customers.
To our knowledge, the very specific conditions are: - the bug only appears on Chrome, not on Safari, FF, or IE. - the bug never appeared on Chrome Mac, but appears under both Chrome Linux and Chrome Windows. - the bug appears on a large size Label created with: label.setFont(new qx.bom.Font(20)); - however these conditions are not sufficient. The bug doesn't seem to appear at all times, but only if we previously did some modifications in the DOM tree, like adding siblings to the BODY element (which we do a lot). - to my eyes, it seems the size of the Label is computed wrong somehow, and therefore the Label decides to use the ellipsis "..." when it shouldn't. - it could be related to differences in font management by Chrome under Mac OS X and Linux/Windows.
Forgot to point out: in my screenshots, the problem lies in the display of the title of the window.

That seems quite obvious why you don't want to show that to your costumers. You description seems to be very hard to reproduce. But in the end, we need to reproduce it as well to get it fixed, especially with that dependency on OS. Have you ever tried to reproduce it in a app you could give us to reproduce?
